Reproducing Results
This guide walks through every step needed to go from raw PhysioNet data to the classification results and figures reported in the paper.

Prerequisites

Python 3.10 or higher
~2 GB disk space for data and figures
Data downloaded to data/raw/ — see DATA.md


1. Set Up the Environment
Create and activate a virtual environment (recommended):
bashpython -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate       # macOS/Linux
.venv\Scripts\activate          # Windows
Install dependencies:
bashpip install -r requirements.txt

2. Preprocess the Data
Load raw WFDB records, segment into analysis windows, reject artifacts, and normalize signals:
bashpython src/preprocess.py
Output: data/processed/windows.pkl — a serialized DataFrame containing one row per analysis window with columns for the raw signal arrays and ground-truth labels.
Expected runtime: 1–3 minutes depending on how many records are present.

3. Extract Features
Apply the full feature engineering pipeline to the processed windows:
bashpython src/features.py
Output: data/processed/features.csv — one row per window, one column per feature, plus a label column (apnea / normal).
Expected runtime: Under 1 minute.

4. Generate Visualizations
Produce all six figures used in the paper:
bashpython src/visualize.py
Output: Six PNG files saved to figures/:
FileFigureumap_condition_type.pngFigure 1 — UMAP colored by condition typeumap_pressure.pngFigure 2 — UMAP colored by pressure levelcorrelation_heatmap.pngFigure 3 — Feature correlation heatmapspo2_distribution.pngFigure 4 — SpO₂ distributions by classumap_apnea_normal.pngFigure 5 — UMAP colored by binary labelfeature_importance.pngFigure 6 — Random Forest feature importances
Expected runtime: 2–5 minutes (UMAP is the slow step).

Note: UMAP results are seeded with random_state=42. Layout will be identical across runs, but may differ from other machines if library versions differ.


5. Train and Evaluate the Classifier
Run the three experiments (respiratory-only, oximetry-only, multimodal) with 5-fold stratified cross-validation:
bashpython src/classify.py
Output: Results printed to stdout and saved to results/classification_report.csv.
Expected output:
Respiratory Only  — Accuracy: 0.72  Sensitivity: 0.68  F1: 0.69
Oximetry Only     — Accuracy: 0.78  Sensitivity: 0.75  F1: 0.76
Multimodal        — Accuracy: 0.91  Sensitivity: 0.89  F1: 0.90
Expected runtime: 2–4 minutes.

6. Run Everything at Once
To run the full pipeline end-to-end in one command:
bashpython src/preprocess.py && \
python src/features.py && \
python src/visualize.py && \
python src/classify.py
Total expected runtime: 5–12 minutes on a modern laptop.

